{"id":"int-fe32d00d","kind":"field_change","created_at":"2026-04-12T20:11:18.030204802Z","actor":"Mark Atwood","issue_id":"FrontierProgrammingLanguageIdeas-w8c","extra":{"field":"status","new_value":"closed","old_value":"open","reason":"Specified pinned type semantics: exhaustive move definition, drop guarantee, automatic noalias suppression (no UnsafePinned needed), generic instantiation failure instead of Unpin, unsafe code contract. Design decision note explains Rust's UnsafePinned lesson and why first-class type property avoids it."}}
{"id":"int-a0615469","kind":"field_change","created_at":"2026-04-12T20:20:09.988588082Z","actor":"Mark Atwood","issue_id":"FrontierProgrammingLanguageIdeas-5k7","extra":{"field":"status","new_value":"closed","old_value":"open","reason":"Added §2.7 '\\! Panic — Sources and Inference': explicit source table (unwrap/expect/panic\\!/assert/indexing), non-sources table (arithmetic wrapping, ? operator, checked_add), closure body inference rule, full iterator chain example, design decision note on wrapping arithmetic preserving \\! Panic as a meaningful annotation."}}
{"id":"int-a8e362ba","kind":"field_change","created_at":"2026-04-12T20:31:14.514074975Z","actor":"Mark Atwood","issue_id":"FrontierProgrammingLanguageIdeas-b1b","extra":{"field":"status","new_value":"closed","old_value":"open","reason":"Added 'Closure Captures and the Effect System' subsection to §2.5: mutation through captures is orthogonal to named effects, tracked by Fn/FnMut/FnOnce hierarchy not the effect system. Table showing the two systems answer different questions. No spec gap — the design is sound; the explanation was missing."}}
{"id":"int-829b1e02","kind":"field_change","created_at":"2026-04-12T20:44:33.117522926Z","actor":"Mark Atwood","issue_id":"FrontierProgrammingLanguageIdeas-bzg","extra":{"field":"status","new_value":"closed","old_value":"open","reason":"Added §2.4 subsections: (1) thread-local mutable state generates ! IO — same rule as process-global state, not suppressible by @pure, with example. (2) @pure and no-alloc contexts — documented acknowledged limitation: @pure is a correctness claim not a resource-usage claim; no-alloc callers must audit @pure callees manually."}}
